{
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "unreal_header_tool",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Unreal Header Tool and Generated Code\nobject_system | P0 | D3\n\nUHT parses supported Unreal declarations and generates support code before normal C++ compilation.\nWhy: It explains reflection syntax, generated-header rules, and a major class of build errors.",
      "x": 0,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_object_lifetime",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "C++ Object Lifetime and Storage\nstandard_cpp | P0 | D4\n\nObjects have typed lifetimes nested within storage duration; surviving addresses and handles can dangle after lifetime ends.\nWhy: Use-after-free, dangling captures, shutdown bugs, and invalid views require reasoning beyond null checks.",
      "x": 0,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "unreal_build_pipeline",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UBT, UHT, Compiler, Linker, and Load Pipeline\nbuild_tools | P0 | D4\n\nClassify UBT graph construction, UHT generation, native compilation, linking, module loading and package stages from their evidence.\nWhy: Build failures persist when unrelated stages are conflated and cascading errors are treated as independent causes.",
      "x": 520,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "iterator_invalidation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Iterator, Pointer, and Reference Invalidation\ncpp_memory_model | P0 | D3\n\nContainer mutation can invalidate element handles even while the container remains alive.\nWhy: Reallocation and erase-related dangling handles are common, intermittent game bugs.",
      "x": 520,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_raii_rule_zero",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "RAII and Rule of Zero/Five\ncpp_memory_model | P0 | D4\n\nBind resources to object lifetime and compose self-managing members; make every special-member operation deliberate when custom ownership is required.\nWhy: It makes cleanup structural and prevents leaks, double release, shallow-copy ownership, and silently suppressed moves.",
      "x": 520,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "unreal_reflection",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Unreal Reflection System\nobject_system | P0 | D4\n\nEngine-visible metadata and generated support for selected classes, structs, enums, properties, and functions.\nWhy: It underpins editor integration, Blueprint exposure, serialisation, replication metadata, and UObject reference discovery.",
      "x": 520,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "module_dependency_api_boundaries",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Module Public/Private Dependency and API Boundaries\nbuild_tools | P0 | D4\n\nDesign Target/ModuleRules, self-contained public headers, private implementation, exports and IWYU/non-unity correctness.\nWhy: Transitive includes and public dependency fan-out create brittle builds, unresolved symbols and slow iteration.",
      "x": 1040,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "uobject",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UObject Model\nobject_system | P0 | D4\n\nUnreal-managed object identity, type data, engine services, and garbage-collected lifetime layered on C++.\nWhy: Most gameplay and editor architecture rests on choosing correctly between UObject, Actor, reflected value, and ordinary C++ type.",
      "x": 1040,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_copy_move",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Copy, Move, and Value Return\nstandard_cpp | P0 | D4\n\nCopy preserves logical value; move enables representation transfer; modern return-by-value relies on elision and implicit move.\nWhy: Correct semantics affect class safety, container compatibility, API clarity, and performance.",
      "x": 1040,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_string_types",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "FName, FString, and FText\nue_cpp_idioms | P0 | D3\n\nChoose identifier, mutable character data, or localisable display text semantics deliberately.\nWhy: Wrong choices create localisation loss, conversion churn, unclear identity, and poor APIs.",
      "x": 1040,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_containers",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "TArray, TSet, and TMap\nue_cpp_idioms | P0 | D4\n\nUnreal value-owning sequence and hash containers with engine reflection/serialisation integration and distinct order/invalidation contracts.\nWhy: Container choice controls access complexity, locality, ordering, reflection support, and handle validity.",
      "x": 1040,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_templates_constraints",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Template Deduction, Forwarding, SFINAE, and Concepts\ncpp | P0 | D4\n\nDesign readable generic APIs using deduction/reference collapsing, one-use perfect forwarding and explicit compile-time requirements.\nWhy: Universal-reference hijacking, double forwarding and opaque substitution failures cause correctness and maintainability problems.",
      "x": 1560,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_ownership",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Unique, Shared, Weak, and Borrowed Ownership\ncpp_memory_model | P0 | D4\n\nDirect values and unique ownership are defaults; shared ownership is explicit co-lifetime, weak edges observe, and raw/reference handles borrow.\nWhy: Ownership ambiguity causes leaks, cycles, premature destruction, unexpected thread destruction, and hot-path overhead.",
      "x": 1560,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "algorithm_complexity_selection",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Algorithm Constraints, Complexity, and Data Selection\ngame_algorithms | P0 | D4\n\nClarify constraints, state a correct baseline/invariant and compare worst, expected and amortised time, space and layout.\nWhy: Strong solutions fit the actual data shape and make assumptions, invalidation and measurement explicit.",
      "x": 1560,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "actor_component_model",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Actor and Component Model\ngameplay_framework | P0 | D4\n\nActors provide independent world identity; Components compose transform-free, spatial, or primitive capabilities into Actors.\nWhy: Correct composition and registration boundaries underpin gameplay, rendering, collision, and replication architecture.",
      "x": 1560,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "uobject_garbage_collection",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UObject Garbage Collection\nmemory_lifetime | P0 | D4\n\nMark-and-sweep reclamation based on reachability through roots and discoverable strong references.\nWhy: Incorrect reference graphs cause disappearing objects, unintended retention, and frame hitches.",
      "x": 1560,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "class_default_object",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Class Default Object and Construction\nobject_system | P0 | D3\n\nEach UClass has a default template object; constructors establish defaults and default subobjects.\nWhy: It prevents world-dependent constructor bugs and explains default propagation and Blueprint class defaults.",
      "x": 1560,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "frame_budget_bottleneck_classification",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Frame Budgets and Bottleneck Classification\nprofiling_optimisation | P0 | D4\n\nDefine frame-time targets and classify Game, Draw, RHI, GPU, memory, I/O, network, or display constraints before detailed analysis.\nWhy: Optimising the wrong lane wastes time and can regress other platforms or quality.",
      "x": 1560,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "audio_sources_component_lifecycle",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Audio Sources, Parameters, and Component Lifetime\naudio | P1 | D4\n\nChoose Wave, Cue or MetaSound and one-shot versus owned AudioComponent with explicit loop, attachment, parameter and teardown policy.\nWhy: Restarted loops, auto-destroy misuse and pooled stale Components create duplicate, missing and detached audio.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_layout_cache_allocators",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "C++ Object Layout, Cache Locality, Arenas, and Pools\ncpp | P1 | D4\n\nReason from size/alignment/padding and access patterns to AoS/SoA/chunk layouts and lifetime-specific allocator choices.\nWhy: Raw-byte assumptions corrupt schemas while unmeasured layouts/pools trade simple ownership for padding, escapes, reset bugs and retained memory.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "sequence_hash_heap_tradeoffs",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Sequences, Hash Tables, Heaps, and Queues\ngame_algorithms | P0 | D4\n\nChoose contiguous sequences, hash indices and priority/FIFO/LIFO structures by dominant access, invalidation and order.\nWhy: Core gameplay structures expose locality, identity, lifetime and deterministic-order judgement.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "spatial_partition_broadphase",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Spatial Partitions, BVHs, and Broadphase\ngame_algorithms | P1 | D4\n\nReduce exact spatial work with conservative candidates selected by distribution, dimension, motion and query/update shape.\nWhy: AI, physics, rendering and networking depend on spatial filtering, but poor policies restore quadratic work.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "math_vectors_projection_orientation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Vectors, Dot/Cross, Projection, and Orientation\ngame_math | P0 | D4\n\nApply length, normalisation, dot/cross, projection/rejection/reflection and signed-angle reasoning under Unreal conventions.\nWhy: Aiming, perception, movement, lighting and geometry all depend on correct magnitude, orientation and zero handling.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "actor_lifecycle",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Actor and Component Lifecycle\ngameplay_framework | P0 | D4\n\nLoaded, duplicated, immediate-spawned, and deferred-spawned Actors follow distinct early paths before component initialisation and play.\nWhy: Wrong-hook code produces CDO/editor side effects, duplicate bindings, unregistered components, and cleanup leaks.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "pawn_controller_possession",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Pawn, Character, Controller, and Possession\ngameplay_framework | P0 | D4\n\nPawns are possessable world agents, Characters add humanoid movement conventions, and Controllers represent player or AI decision sources.\nWhy: The separation enables respawn, spectating, vehicle changes, AI/human reuse, and correct network responsibility placement.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "uobject_pointer_selection",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UObject Pointer Selection\nmemory_lifetime | P0 | D4\n\nChoose raw, TObjectPtr, weak, soft, or strong references from retention and loading intent.\nWhy: The wrong pointer expresses the wrong lifetime/dependency contract even when code appears to work.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "timing_insights",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Timing Insights and Scoped Instrumentation\nprofiling_optimisation | P0 | D4\n\nCapture aligned thread/task/GPU traces, compare frames, inspect scopes/callers/counts, and add targeted project instrumentation.\nWhy: It turns a high-level bottleneck into a causal call path and measurable intervention.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_delegates",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Native, Multicast, and Dynamic Delegates\nue_cpp_idioms | P0 | D4\n\nSelect callback cardinality, reflection capability, and lifetime-aware binding independently.\nWhy: Delegate misuse causes dangling callbacks, duplicate invocation, hidden reflection cost, and lifecycle leaks.",
      "x": 2080,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ai_controller_decision_architecture",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "AIController and Decision Architecture\nai_navigation | P1 | D4\n\nSeparate controller decision policy from Pawn physical capabilities and decompose sensing, memory, decisions, queries, paths, and steering.\nWhy: Layer separation makes systems reusable and lets failures be localised instead of blamed on the whole AI.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "audio_classes_submix_dsp",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Sound Classes, Mixes, Submix Routing, and DSP\naudio | P1 | D4\n\nSeparate semantic category control from actual dry/send signal routing and per-source versus shared submix DSP.\nWhy: Undocumented routes cause silent/doubled signals, stuck ducking and per-voice effects that scale badly.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "live_coding_reinstancing",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Live Coding, Reinstancing, and Clean-Restart Boundaries\nbuild_tools | P1 | D4\n\nUse binary patching for iteration while treating reflected layout, defaults/subobjects, build graph and static lifetime as restart/rebuild proof boundaries.\nWhy: Stale UObject/static caches and old/new destructor/layout state can corrupt assets or crash long after a seemingly successful patch.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_memory_model_synchronisation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "C++ Data Races, Mutexes, Condition Variables, and Atomics\ncpp | P0 | D4\n\nEstablish happens-before for compound invariants using ownership/mutexes and use atomics/memory order only for a written publication/counter protocol.\nWhy: Data races are UB; volatile, several atomics or notifications without predicate state do not create correct synchronisation.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_lambdas_callable_erasure",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Lambda Capture Lifetime and Callable Type Erasure\ncpp | P0 | D4\n\nSelect explicit safe captures and choose templates, function pointers, type-erased wrappers or Unreal delegates from lifetime/runtime semantics.\nWhy: Delayed captures dangle or retain worlds, while unnecessary owning erasure adds copies/allocations/indirection and empty-call hazards.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "blueprint_api_design",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "C++ and Blueprint API Boundary\ncpp_blueprint | P0 | D4\n\nKeep stable invariants and authority in narrow native APIs while exposing designer-owned data, composition, and bounded extension to Blueprint.\nWhy: A deliberate boundary improves iteration, testability, authority, performance visibility, and packaged-build reliability.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "sorting_binary_search_patterns",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Sorting, Binary Search, and Sequence Patterns\ngame_algorithms | P0 | D4\n\nUse strict ordering and half-open search invariants, performing only the ordering/selection the output needs.\nWhy: Boundary/comparator errors are common and unnecessary full sorts waste work.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "math_spaces_transforms_matrices",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Coordinate Spaces, Transforms, Matrices, and Normals\ngame_math | P0 | D4\n\nDistinguish points/vectors/normals and compose/invert local/world transforms with explicit convention/order.\nWhy: Space and transform-order bugs cause attachment, aiming, animation and rendering failures that look unrelated.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "math_kinematics_numerical_robustness",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Kinematics, Units, Precision, and Numerical Robustness\ngame_math | P0 | D4\n\nTrack dimensions/timestep and defend calculations against degeneracy, NaN, tolerance and large-coordinate precision loss.\nWhy: Frame-rate dependence and numeric edge cases become jitter, tunnelling and nondeterministic movement.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gameplay_framework_state_roles",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GameMode, GameState, PlayerController, and PlayerState\ngameplay_framework | P0 | D4\n\nFramework classes divide server-only rules, shared match state, owning-player control, and broadly replicated participant state.\nWhy: Lifetime and network audience mistakes commonly work standalone and fail in multiplayer or across respawn.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "component_contracts_composition",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Component Contracts and Composition\npatterns_architecture | P0 | D4\n\nCompose coherent capabilities with explicit owner, lifecycle, authority, replication and dependency contracts instead of subclass or cast webs.\nWhy: Composition is Unreal's common reuse unit but hidden sibling/global coupling can recreate a monolith.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "physics_filtering_geometry",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Collision Filtering, Profiles, and Simple/Complex Geometry\nphysics | P1 | D4\n\nPredict query/simulation participation from collision enabled, Object Type, bilateral/channel responses, named profiles and actual simple/complex shapes.\nWhy: Most collision bugs are policy/geometry mismatches hidden by Actor-level assumptions or ad-hoc overrides.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gameplay_cpu_optimisation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Gameplay CPU Scheduling and Data Optimisation\nprofiling_optimisation | P1 | D4\n\nOptimise measured frequency, algorithms, allocation, locality, duplication and synchronisation using Tick/events/timers/batching appropriately.\nWhy: Most gameplay CPU regressions are multiplicative count/frequency/data problems rather than one slow function.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 2640,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "memory_gc_profiling",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Memory Insights, Allocation Churn, and GC\nprofiling_optimisation | P1 | D4\n\nInvestigate capacity, growth, short/long-lived allocation churn, retention and GC spikes across repeatable lifecycle markers.\nWhy: Memory bugs cause crashes, hitches, fragmentation, streaming churn, and hidden CPU cost.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 2860,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "render_pipeline_passes",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Render Pipeline, RHI, and GPU Passes\nrendering | P1 | D4\n\nRelate overlapping Game/Render/RHI/GPU lanes to view construction and depth, shadow, base/GBuffer, lighting, translucency and post passes.\nWhy: A pass-level frame model is required to localise rendering regressions and communicate across gameplay, engine and art roles.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 3080,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_vs_uobject_lifetime",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Standard C++ versus UObject Lifetime Domains\nue_cpp_idioms | P0 | D4\n\nRAII/reference-counted ordinary objects and reachability-collected UObjects use different ownership and observation mechanisms.\nWhy: Pointer names look similar, but crossing domains incorrectly creates leaks, invalid references, and false thread-safety assumptions.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 3300,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_creation_and_casts",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UObject/Actor Creation and Runtime Casts\nue_cpp_idioms | P0 | D4\n\nCreation APIs select UObject, Actor, deferred-spawn, or class-default-subobject lifecycle; Cast performs checked UObject conversion.\nWhy: Wrong APIs bypass lifecycle contracts, while repeated type discovery creates architectural coupling.",
      "x": 2600,
      "y": 3520,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ai_perception_memory",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "AI Perception and Stimulus Memory\nai_navigation | P1 | D4\n\nConfigured senses receive stimuli events; explicit memory policy distinguishes currently perceived, known, last-known, and forgotten state.\nWhy: Incorrect stimulus lifecycle creates psychic AI, instant forgetting, and decision churn.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "behavior_tree_blackboard",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Behaviour Tree, Blackboard, and Observer Aborts\nai_navigation | P1 | D4\n\nEvent-driven priority/action selection using Blackboard memory, tasks, decorators, services, and abort-aware branch changes.\nWhy: Correct node/lifecycle design gives responsive, debuggable AI without per-frame tree polling.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "audio_spatial_concurrency_voices",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Audio Spatialisation, Concurrency, and Voice Admission\naudio | P1 | D4\n\nMap listener-relative attenuation/focus/occlusion into semantic concurrency, priority, stealing and virtual voice policy.\nWhy: A requested source may be inaudible because of listener gain or admission; uncontrolled emitters overwhelm voices and queries.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_odr_linking_sanitizers",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "ODR, Linkage, Static Initialisation, and Sanitizers\ncpp | P0 | D4\n\nDiagnose symbols/translation units/modules from ODR and linkage, control global startup, and use ASan/TSan/UBSan as bounded dynamic evidence.\nWhy: Header definitions, hidden templates/exports and global constructor order create build/startup failures that clean rebuilds do not explain.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cpp_tasks_parallelism",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Task Graphs, Parallel Partitioning, Cancellation, and Merge\ncpp | P1 | D4\n\nExpress DAG dependencies over immutable/partitioned work, local outputs and deterministic merge without blocking workers or violating Game Thread affinity.\nWhy: Tiny/chatty tasks, shared-output locks, stale captures and wait cycles erase parallel gains or deadlock/crash after travel.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ecs_mass_actor_tradeoff",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "ECS/MassEntity versus Actor Architecture\necs_mass | P2 | D4\n\nChoose Mass for large stable batchable data populations and Actors for rich independent UObject world behaviour, using hybrid representation where justified.\nWhy: Fashion-driven ECS adoption adds plugin/tooling complexity without performance if access patterns remain object-oriented.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "graph_search_connectivity",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Graph Traversal, Shortest Paths, DAGs, and Connectivity\ngame_algorithms | P0 | D4\n\nChoose BFS/DFS/Dijkstra/A* by cost semantics, topological order for DAGs and DSU for incremental connectivity.\nWhy: Navigation/dependency algorithms fail silently when weights, heuristics, cycles or deletion constraints are wrong.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "math_intersections_sweeps",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Closest Points, Ray Intersections, Bounds, and Sweeps\ngame_math | P0 | D4\n\nDerive primitive tests by substitution/projection and filter line solutions by ray/segment intervals and degeneracy policy.\nWhy: Targeting, collision and culling require correct tangent/inside/parallel/behind handling, not only happy-path formulas.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "math_rotations_interpolation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Rotators, Quaternions, and Interpolation\ngame_math | P0 | D4\n\nUse Euler/Rotator parameters for readable constraints and unit quaternions/Slerp for robust 3D composition, distinguishing easing from constant speed.\nWhy: Angle wrap, gimbal singularity, quaternion sign/order and frame-rate-dependent smoothing are common gameplay defects.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "math_rendering_spaces_colour_depth",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Rendering Spaces, Tangent Basis, Depth, and Linear Colour\ngame_math | P1 | D4\n\nTrack local→world→view→clip→NDC→screen and treat tangent normals, projected depth and linear colour with correct conventions.\nWhy: Shader/UI projection, normal-map and colour/depth bugs come from mixing coordinate and encoding domains.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "subsystem_lifetimes",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Subsystem Lifetimes and Service Placement\ngameplay_architecture | P1 | D4\n\nSubsystems are auto-instanced services scoped to Engine, Editor, GameInstance, World, or LocalPlayer hosts.\nWhy: Choosing the narrowest correct host avoids global-state leaks and supports multi-world and multi-player correctness.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "enhanced_input_actions_values",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Enhanced Input Actions and Value Semantics\nmodern_ue5 | P1 | D3\n\nModel input as semantic actions with typed values, separate from device keys and gameplay authority.\nWhy: Device-named bindings and value-type confusion make remapping, UI modes, gamepad parity and network validation brittle.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "data_driven_definitions_state",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Data-driven Definitions, Runtime State, and Presentation\npatterns_architecture | P0 | D4\n\nSeparate validated authored definitions with stable asset identity from mutable per-instance state and local presentation/loading.\nWhy: Content scale, save compatibility, replication, loading and designer workflows fail when definitions and runtime state are mixed.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 2640,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "state_strategy_policy",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "State, Strategy, and Policy Selection\npatterns_architecture | P1 | D4\n\nUse State for modes/transitions and Strategy for interchangeable policies, retaining simple branches for small stable variants.\nWhy: Boolean state explosions and giant variation switches produce invalid combinations and unsafe extension points.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 2860,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "render_cost_dimensions",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Rendering Cost Dimensions and Pass-led Diagnosis\nrendering | P0 | D4\n\nSeparate CPU submission, geometry, pixel/fill, shader, overdraw and bandwidth pressure and test pass-mechanism hypotheses.\nWhy: Optimisations fail when draw calls, polygons, materials and fill rate are treated as one generic graphics cost.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 3080,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "rdg_resources_dependencies",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "RDG Passes, Resources, and Dependencies\nrendering | P2 | D4\n\nDeclare deferred render passes and resource access so RDG can derive lifetimes, transitions, culling, aliasing and scheduling.\nWhy: Renderer extensions require correct deferred lifetimes and complete resource contracts before low-level optimisation is safe.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 3300,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_specifier_metadata_contracts",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UE Specifiers and Metadata by Consuming System\nue_cpp_idioms | P0 | D4\n\nClassify UCLASS/USTRUCT/UFUNCTION/UPROPERTY specifiers and metadata by the engine system that consumes them.\nWhy: Specifier cargo-culting leaks authority, persistence, Blueprint API and editor behaviour into the wrong layer.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 3520,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_core_vocabulary_lifetime",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UE Core Vocabulary Types and Non-Owning Lifetimes\nue_cpp_idioms | P1 | D4\n\nUse TOptional, TVariant, TFunctionRef and view-like APIs to express absence, closed alternatives, synchronous callbacks and contiguous borrowed storage.\nWhy: Vocabulary types make contracts explicit but can create dangling views/callables when stored or used asynchronously.",
      "x": 3120,
      "y": 3740,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "smart_object_affordance_slots",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Smart Object Affordances, Definitions, and Slots\nai_navigation | P2 | D3\n\nRepresent world opportunities as authored definitions/components with slots, activity tags, user requirements and behavior references.\nWhy: Reusable interactions collapse into brittle Actor-specific scripts unless the affordance and slot contract is explicit.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "statetree_fsm_comparison",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "StateTree, Behaviour Tree, and FSM Trade-offs\nai_navigation | P2 | D3\n\nChoose reactive priority trees, hierarchical state/transition selection, or small explicit state machines according to semantics and tooling.\nWhy: Fashion-driven decision frameworks create avoidable complexity and migration cost.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "asset_references_dependency_closure",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Hard/Soft References and Dependency Closure\nassets_loading | P0 | D4\n\nChoose hard, soft-class/object and weak references from identity, co-residency and lifetime needs while auditing transitive dependency closure.\nWhy: A small root can accidentally load large content graphs, while soft references alone do not solve cook or residency.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "mass_fragments_archetypes_chunks",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Mass Fragments, Tags, Archetypes, and Chunks\necs_mass | P2 | D3\n\nCompose data-only entities from fragments/tags and store identical compositions in archetype chunks with per-entity/shared/chunk cardinality.\nWhy: Fragment boundaries and composition cardinality determine cache efficiency, archetype count and structural cost.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "algorithm_differential_verification",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Algorithm Invariants, Differential Testing, and Benchmarks\ngame_algorithms | P0 | D4\n\nProve optimised structures against simple oracles on adversarial generated inputs and benchmark phases separately.\nWhy: Fast wrong algorithms and average-only benchmarks are worse than simple reliable baselines.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_native_gc_bridge_thread_boundaries",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Native GC Bridges and UObject Thread Boundaries\nmemory_lifetime | P1 | D4\n\nUse FGCObject or other explicit retention only for native owners that cannot be reflected, and keep off-thread work on plain snapshots with Game Thread revalidation.\nWhy: Native owners and tasks are common places for hidden UObject retention, early collection, stale captures and wrong-thread crashes.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "enhanced_input_mapping_contexts",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Enhanced Input Mapping Contexts and LocalPlayer Lifecycle\nmodern_ue5 | P1 | D4\n\nApply, prioritise and remove Mapping Contexts on the LocalPlayer subsystem according to mode, possession and UI state.\nWhy: Stale contexts cause double fire, lost controls, split-screen leakage and UI/gameplay conflicts.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "enhanced_input_modifiers_triggers",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Enhanced Input Modifiers and Triggers\nmodern_ue5 | P1 | D4\n\nUse Modifiers to transform sampled values and Triggers to decide when an action becomes started, ongoing, triggered, completed or canceled.\nWhy: Putting dead zones, chord rules and hold thresholds in ad hoc gameplay code makes behaviour inconsistent across devices and contexts.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "subsystem_service_boundaries",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Subsystem and Service Boundaries\npatterns_architecture | P1 | D4\n\nChoose a scoped subsystem host deliberately and keep retrieval near composition boundaries when hidden dependencies harm testing or world correctness.\nWhy: Subsystem convenience can turn into wrong-lifetime global state and invisible god-service coupling.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "physics_scene_queries_hits_events",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Scene Queries, Hit Results, and Collision Event Semantics\nphysics | P1 | D4\n\nChoose channel/object line/sweep/overlap queries and interpret components, initial penetration, contact data and non-exactly-once callbacks.\nWhy: Wrong query volume/filter and callback assumptions cause missed targets, duplicate damage and opaque interaction bugs.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "geometry_representation_nanite_lod",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Culling, Instancing, LOD, HLOD, and Nanite\nrendering | P1 | D4\n\nChoose a geometry representation by submission, visibility, detail, streaming, material/deformation and target-platform constraints.\nWhy: Modern UE geometry choices trade CPU scene cost, GPU visibility/raster cost, memory, culling granularity and authoring flexibility.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "lumen_scene_tracing",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Lumen GI and Reflection Diagnosis\nrendering | P1 | D4\n\nDiagnose dynamic GI/reflection quality and cost across screen traces, software/hardware tracing and Lumen scene/surface representations.\nWhy: Lumen artefacts and cost often originate in representation or tracing mode rather than a single generic quality slider.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "materials_permutations_translucency",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Materials, Shader Permutations, WPO, and Translucency\nrendering | P1 | D4\n\nChoose dynamic parameters, bounded static variants and surface modes while accounting for runtime shading, overdraw, bounds and build/PSO costs.\nWhy: Materials affect pixel/vertex work, passes, shadows, culling, shader libraries and runtime pipeline diversity.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 2640,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_logging_assert_diagnostics",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UE Logging and Assertion Diagnostics\nue_cpp_idioms | P0 | D4\n\nUse log categories/verbosity/structured fields and choose check, verify and ensure by invariant and build behaviour.\nWhy: Good diagnostics preserve correlation evidence; wrong assertions crash recoverable paths or remove required side effects.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 2860,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ui_umg_slate_lifecycle",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UMG, Slate, and Widget Lifecycle\nui | P1 | D4\n\nSeparate UUserWidget UObject lifetime, underlying Slate construction and repeatable screen activation with symmetric ownership and teardown.\nWhy: Treating Construct as BeginPlay causes duplicate delegates, retained screens and stale callbacks across rebuild/travel.",
      "x": 3640,
      "y": 3080,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "animation_assets_skeleton_retarget",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Animation Assets, Skeletons, Compression, and Retargeting\nanimation | P1 | D4\n\nManage Skeletal Mesh/Skeleton/Sequence schema, additive/root metadata, compression and IK-retarget roots/chains/poses.\nWhy: Asset/reference/retarget mistakes propagate into every runtime pose and are often misdiagnosed as graph bugs.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "async_asset_request_lifecycle",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Async Asset Request and Residency Lifecycle\nassets_loading | P0 | D4\n\nScope asynchronous loads with handles/generations, weak owners, cancellation/failure states and explicit post-completion residency.\nWhy: Late callbacks, replaced requests, travel and released temporary ownership produce stale updates and unloaded assets.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "asset_registry_manager_bundles",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Asset Registry, Asset Manager, Primary Assets, and Bundles\nassets_loading | P1 | D4\n\nUse Registry metadata for unloaded discovery and Asset Manager Primary identity/rules/bundles for managed loading and cook policy.\nWhy: Discovery, identity, loading and cook management are distinct responsibilities often conflated in weak designs.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "pcg_graph_points_attributes",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "PCG Graphs, Points, Density, and Attributes\nassets_loading | P2 | D4\n\nModel PCG as spatial data flowing from a Component through graph nodes into points with density, metadata domains and generated output.\nWhy: Procedural tools become unshippable when point data, density, attributes and generated ownership are treated as random scatter.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "audio_timing_streaming_memory",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Audio Timing, Quartz, Streaming, and Memory\naudio | P2 | D4\n\nDistinguish frame/buffer/sample timing and asset/chunk/decoded residency while balancing latency, I/O, cache and memory.\nWhy: Loaded assets can miss cold playback, cache churn can underrun and game timers cannot guarantee musical/sample timing.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "render_shader_pso_pipeline",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Shader Permutations and PSO Cache Workflow\nrendering | P1 | D4\n\nSeparate compiled shader variants, runtime shader cost and first-use Pipeline State Object creation/cache coverage.\nWhy: Shader and PSO problems cause build pain, memory/library growth and runtime hitches that require different evidence and fixes.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "vsm_pages_invalidation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Virtual Shadow Map Pages and Invalidation\nrendering | P1 | D4\n\nReason about demand-allocated cached shadow pages, new visibility, moving lights/casters, WPO and non-Nanite shadow submission.\nWhy: VSM regressions are often cache-invalidation and affected-page problems rather than only generic shadow quality cost.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "render_mesh_draw_command_pipeline",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Mesh Drawing Pipeline and Draw Command Pressure\nrendering | P2 | D4\n\nUnderstand how primitives become scene proxies, mesh batches and pass-specific cached or dynamic draw commands.\nWhy: Gameplay-side component, material-slot and render-state decisions can create render-thread/Draw/RHI cost before the GPU is the limiter.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_persistence_property_flags",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Config, SaveGame, Transient, and Duplication Boundaries\nue_cpp_idioms | P0 | D4\n\nSeparate class defaults, config, runtime, save-game, duplicated and transient cache state.\nWhy: Many packaged, PIE and save/load bugs come from assuming one property flag designs the whole persistence path.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ui_layout_localisation_accessibility",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Responsive UI Layout, Localisation, and Accessibility\nui | P1 | D4\n\nReason from desired size and parent constraints through anchors, DPI, safe zones, culture-aware text and accessible interaction.\nWhy: Fixed English-only Canvas layouts fail across aspect, device, culture, input and user needs.",
      "x": 4160,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "world_level_streaming_lifetime",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Level and World Partition Streaming Lifetime\nassets_loading | P1 | D4\n\nDesign streaming sources/readiness, spatial loading, cross-cell references and durable state/async cleanup across world regions.\nWhy: Unloaded Actors, teleport races and cross-cell dependencies cause correctness failures beyond simple memory optimisation.",
      "x": 4680,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "pcg_debug_reproducibility",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "PCG Debugging and Reproducibility\nassets_loading | P2 | D4\n\nFreeze seed, graph version, inputs and parameters, then inspect point counts, density, transforms, attributes and node phases to find the first contradiction.\nWhy: Procedural bugs cannot be fixed reliably without reproducible inputs and phase-by-phase evidence.",
      "x": 4680,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "blueprint_async_proxy_lifetime",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Async Blueprint Proxy Lifetime and Cancellation\ncpp_blueprint | P1 | D4\n\nDesign async Blueprint nodes around proxy retention, activation, cancellation, stale-generation rejection, Game Thread completion and cleanup.\nWhy: Async teaching examples often compile while leaking proxies, collecting them early or broadcasting after travel/destruction.",
      "x": 4680,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_object_identity_apis_flags",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UObject Identity, Object APIs, Outer, Packages, Names, and Flags\nobject_system | P0 | D4\n\nChoose NewObject, SpawnActor, lookup, load and duplicate paths by intent while separating Outer identity from retention.\nWhy: Wrong object API or Outer mental model causes missing GC edges, skipped Actor lifecycle, blocking loads and duplicate graph corruption.",
      "x": 4680,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "render_targets_scene_captures",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Render Targets and Scene Capture Budgets\nrendering | P1 | D4\n\nBudget render targets and scene captures by memory, bandwidth, update cadence, view count, format, mips/copies/readbacks and consumers.\nWhy: Mirrors, minimaps, thumbnails, security cameras and UI previews can secretly add extra views, PSOs, memory and first-use hitches.",
      "x": 4680,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "render_global_shader_plugin_workflow",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Global Shader and Plugin Shader Workflow\nrendering | P2 | D4\n\nAdd custom global/plugin shaders with correct source mapping, module registration, permutation predicates, RDG parameters and output validation.\nWhy: Renderer/tool extensions often fail from load order, shader path, permutation, parameter or deferred-lifetime mistakes before the algorithm matters.",
      "x": 4680,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ui_input_focus_commonui",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UI Hit Testing, Focus, Navigation, and CommonUI\nui | P1 | D4\n\nCoordinate per-user focus, hit testing, navigation, modal restoration and one owner for activatable input configuration.\nWhy: Invisible interceptors and competing input-mode owners create controller soft-locks and local multiplayer failures.",
      "x": 4680,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "render_gpu_capture_workflow",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "RenderDoc and Platform GPU Capture Workflow\nrendering | P2 | D4\n\nEscalate from Unreal pass timings to external GPU captures when exact pipeline state, resources, shaders or platform behaviour must be inspected.\nWhy: Engine pass timings localise cost, but GPU captures are often required to diagnose binding, shader, occupancy, barrier or RHI/vendor issues.",
      "x": 5200,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "world_partition_grid_sources",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "World Partition Grid, Streaming Sources, and Spatial Actor Policy\nworld_building | P2 | D4\n\nDesign grid/source/readiness policy, spatial versus always-loaded Actors and cross-cell reference constraints for large UE5 worlds.\nWhy: World Partition automates cell streaming but does not decide durable state, teleport readiness, reference hygiene or target performance for the project.",
      "x": 5200,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "world_ofpa_level_instance_collaboration",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "OFPA, Level Instances, and Reusable POI Collaboration\nworld_building | P2 | D3\n\nUse OFPA to reduce edit conflicts and choose Level Instances or Packed Level Blueprints from reuse, density, runtime mode and identity needs.\nWhy: Large-world authoring fails when source-control storage, reusable POIs and runtime gameplay identity are treated as the same problem.",
      "x": 5720,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ai_custom_sense_pipeline",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Custom AI Sense Pipeline\nai_navigation | P2 | D4\n\nDesign custom perception channels as batched evidence producers that emit stimuli without owning final decisions.\nWhy: Custom senses easily become hidden gameplay state machines or hot-loop trace floods unless source, sense, memory and decision responsibilities are separated.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ai_perception_memory_projection_specialist",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Perception Memory Projection and Evidence Decay\nai_navigation | P2 | D4\n\nMerge sight, hearing, damage and custom stimuli into explicit current, known, last-evidence and confidence state with decay.\nWhy: Most stealth/investigation bugs come from treating one stimulus callback as the whole target truth.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "animation_debug_profile_budget",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Animation Debugging, Profiling, LOD, and Budgeting\nanimation | P1 | D4\n\nDiagnose values, relevance and pose influence over time, then budget game/worker/finalise/skinning/query/asset layers by significance.\nWhy: Many-character animation cost spans CPU/render/assets and naive throttling breaks critical pose/timing behaviour.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "animation_runtime_threads_snapshot",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Animation Runtime, Worker Threads, and Gameplay Snapshot\nanimation | P1 | D4\n\nSeparate game-thread EventGraph data gathering from worker-safe update/evaluation and give pose logic a compact stable snapshot.\nWhy: Unsafe UObject access and per-character polling cause races, warnings and game-thread scaling failures.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "animation_state_blend_sync",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Animation State Machines, Blend Spaces, Layers, and Sync\nanimation | P1 | D4\n\nBuild persistent pose regimes from cheap transitions, calibrated Blend Spaces, deliberate per-bone/additive order and gait-phase sync.\nWhy: State explosion, wrong spaces/ranges and unsynchronised phases produce brittle graphs and visible locomotion defects.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "animation_montage_notify_contract",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Montages, Slots, Sections, and Notify Contracts\nanimation | P1 | D4\n\nPresent directed actions through relevant slots/sections and treat notifies as correlated timing/cosmetic signals, not durable authority.\nWhy: Invisible montages, interruption leaks and notify-owned damage/ammo are common production and interview failures.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "animation_rootmotion_movement_network",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Root Motion, CharacterMovement, and Network Authority\nanimation | P1 | D4\n\nChoose in-place versus authored displacement per action and coordinate extraction, capsule collision, authority, prediction and correction.\nWhy: Dual movement writers and unvalidated root-motion actions create drift, snapping, collision and network exploits.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "animation_linked_layers_ik_warp",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Linked Animation Layers, IK, Control Rig, and Motion Warping\nanimation | P2 | D4\n\nModularise semantic pose layers and apply procedural goals/warp windows with explicit spaces, order, limits, lifetime and LOD.\nWhy: Modular assets can defeat streaming, while wrong-space/ordered procedural solves cause costly unstable poses.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "asset_data_validation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Asset Data Validation and Explicit Repair\neditor_tools | P1 | D4\n\nRun deterministic side-effect-free asset invariants on save/manual/CI and keep repair in separately previewed transactional tools.\nWhy: Early actionable content failures prevent runtime/cook regressions while silent validator mutation makes CI and source control unsafe.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "android_gpu_renderpass_counters",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Android GPU Render-Pass and Counter Diagnosis\nplatform_profiling | P2 | D4\n\nUse AGI frame profiling and vendor-sensitive counters to map mobile GPU cost back to Unreal passes, materials, render targets and geometry.\nWhy: Mobile GPU regressions are often bandwidth, render-pass, overdraw or shader issues that are invisible from average FPS alone.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "android_lmk_thermal_adpf",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Android LMK, Thermal Behavior, and ADPF Evidence\nplatform_profiling | P2 | D4\n\nCorrelate Android LMK/vitals, lifecycle memory, thermal headroom/status and ADPF scalability/performance hints with Unreal memory and performance evidence.\nWhy: A game can pass short foreground FPS tests while failing warm return, memory pressure, sustained thermals or quality-stability requirements.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "android_profiler_correlation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Android Profiler Correlation for Unreal\nplatform_profiling | P2 | D4\n\nCorrelate Unreal stats/CSV/Insights with Android APA/AGI system traces to distinguish engine ownership from device, GPU, OS and present-wait behavior.\nWhy: Android total CPU time, GPU queue pressure, thermal state and driver behavior can contradict naive engine-only conclusions.",
      "x": 6240,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "cooking_packaging_asset_debugging",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Cooking, Packaging, Chunks, Redirectors, and DDC\nassets_loading | P1 | D4\n\nSeparate build/cook/stage/package/deploy and diagnose target inclusion, chunks, moves and derived-data effects from logs/manifests.\nWhy: Editor success hides uncooked assets, stale paths, platform formats and cold derived-data failures.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "audio_network_debug_profile",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Networked Audio Presentation, Debugging, and Profiling\naudio | P1 | D4\n\nReplicate semantics rather than Components, deduplicate prediction and diagnose request-to-output while profiling populations, DSP, cache and callback headroom.\nWhy: Multicast-only audio fails late join and duplicates owners; stage-blind tuning misses admission, routing or data failures.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "buildgraph_release_automation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "AutomationTool, BuildGraph, and Release Gates\nbuild_tools | P2 | D4\n\nModel release automation as explicit build, cook, stage/package, validation, smoke and artifact graph operations rather than editor-local success.\nWhy: A release pipeline must prove reproducibility, dependency order, artifact ownership and clean-machine behaviour before distribution.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ci_matrix_clean_machine_packaging",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "CI Matrix and Clean-Machine Packaging Proof\nbuild_tools | P2 | D4\n\nSplit CI into fast pre-submit, nightly clean, release-candidate and platform/certification tiers with explicit runtime, artifacts and owners.\nWhy: A practical CI matrix catches editor-local assumptions without making every commit pay full release cost.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "csharp_managed_native_interop",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "C# Managed Lifetime, Marshalling, Delegates, and Async\ncsharp | P3 | D4\n\nBridge moving managed GC and native Unreal ownership with explicit ABI, handles, deterministic resource/callback teardown and Game Thread dispatch.\nWhy: Wrong bool/layout, unrooted callbacks, long pinning, unmanaged exceptions and Task continuations cause data corruption or crashes.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "csharp_unreal_hosting_packaging",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "C# Runtime Hosting, UnrealCLR, AOT, and Packaging\ncsharp | P3 | D3\n\nEvaluate a specific .NET host/integration across runtime configuration, API coverage, assembly lifecycle, JIT/AOT, staging, symbols and platform policy.\nWhy: Desktop editor success says little about packaged server, console/mobile, trimming, dynamic loading or long-term servicing.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "editor_automation_surfaces",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Editor Automation Surfaces and Safe Batch Tools\neditor_tools | P1 | D4\n\nChoose Utility Widget, Python, C++ extension or commandlet and share a dry-run/transactional/idempotent operation core across UI and CI.\nWhy: Unsafe batch tools can corrupt thousands of assets faster than manual workflows and are difficult to recover without audit/source-control design.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "character_movement_prediction",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Character Movement Prediction and Reconciliation\nnetworking | P1 | D3\n\nAutonomous clients predict and save moves; the server reproduces/validates; clients correct and replay; simulated proxies smooth updates.\nWhy: It explains responsive movement, corrections, and why direct transform manipulation fights built-in networking.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "device_lab_matrix_manifests",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Device Lab Matrix and Run Manifests\nplatform_release | P2 | D4\n\nDefine a small target-device/scenario matrix and bind every run to build, device, scenario, command line, install mode and output artifacts.\nWhy: Device-only failures are hard to reproduce unless the evidence packet preserves exact identity and environment.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "csv_performance_regression_gates",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "CSV Performance Regression Gates\nprofiling_optimisation | P2 | D4\n\nUse lightweight CSV telemetry and automation scenarios to detect drift, then escalate failures to targeted causal captures.\nWhy: Performance CI must catch real regressions without making every change pay full profiler/capture cost or fail on noise.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "device_lab_telemetry_artifact_harvest",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Device Lab Telemetry and Artifact Harvesting\nprofiling_optimisation | P2 | D4\n\nCollect logs, CSV, profile proof, screenshots, selected traces, crash reports and manifests with the correct run identity.\nWhy: Frequent lightweight telemetry detects regressions while selective traces provide causal evidence without overwhelming the lab.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "device_lab_flake_triage_gate_promotion",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Flaky Device Triage and Gate Promotion\nprofiling_optimisation | P2 | D4\n\nClassify failures as product, infrastructure, flaky device or reporting-only noise, and promote metrics to blocking gates only after variance and ownership are understood.\nWhy: Unclassified red device runs either block real releases with noise or hide deterministic product failures behind reruns.",
      "x": 6760,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "eqs_queries",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Environment Query System\nai_navigation | P1 | D3\n\nGenerators create candidates, Contexts provide reference frames, and Tests filter/score environmental choices.\nWhy: EQS makes spatial decisions data-driven but can become trace/path-query expensive at scale.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_ability_specs_lifecycle",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Ability Specs, Activation, Commit, and Ending\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nAuthority grants specs/handles; activation checks policy, commits deliberately, runs scoped work and always converges on cleanup/end.\nWhy: Duplicate grants, premature costs and leaked active abilities are common production failures.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_adoption_asc_lifetime",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Adoption and ASC Owner/Avatar Lifetime\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nChoose GAS from rule/network density and place/initialise the ASC according to owner state lifetime and current avatar.\nWhy: A needless framework taxes a small project, while wrong ASC placement/actor info breaks activation, respawn and prediction.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_attribute_invariant_matrix",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Attribute Invariant Matrix\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nProve attribute rules across instant, duration, periodic, predicted, replicated and UI-observed mutation paths.\nWhy: A single clamp callback rarely covers all base/current/replication/effect paths that can change combat state.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_effects_stacking",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Gameplay Effects, Specs, Captures, and Stacking\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nSeparate data definitions, application specs and active effects; design lifetime, capture, calculation and stacking policy explicitly.\nWhy: Ambiguous capture/stack/period policy produces incorrect combat and opaque replicated state.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_grant_source_ledger",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Grant Source Ledger\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nTrack ability grants by authority source and spec handle so startup, equipment and temporary grants are idempotent and removable.\nWhy: Removing by ability class fails when several systems grant the same ability or rebuild loadouts after possession/respawn.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_prediction_side_effect_ledger",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Prediction Side-Effect Ledger\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nClassify every predicted ability side effect as supported GAS prediction, cosmetic, reversible custom work or server-only truth.\nWhy: Most prediction failures come from custom side effects that GAS cannot automatically reconcile.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_prediction_replication",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Prediction, Reconciliation, and Effect Replication\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nCorrelate supported provisional owner actions by prediction key while server validates; choose GE replication detail by audience.\nWhy: Prediction mistakes duplicate or leak state, while wrong replication mode either hides needed detail or wastes bandwidth.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_specialist_evidence_contract",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Specialist Evidence Contract\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nTrace GAS activation, target validation, effects, tasks, cues, prediction and UI updates with shared correlation fields.\nWhy: GAS bugs often span client prediction, server validation, active effects and presentation; without correlated evidence teams guess.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_tags_attributes",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Tags, Attributes, and Invariants\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nUse counted hierarchical tags for semantic predicates and Attribute Sets for effect-aware numeric state with complete invariants.\nWhy: Tag-count leaks and inconsistent base/current/clamp paths cause blocked abilities and divergent UI/gameplay state.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gameplay_transactions_persistence",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Gameplay Transactions, Revisions, and Persistence\ngameplay_system_design | P0 | D4\n\nDesign authoritative commands, read-only queries, committed deltas/revisions and versioned stable-ID records for inventory, quests, interaction and save/load.\nWhy: Duplication, stale UI, missed objectives and broken saves are protocol/identity failures more often than container-choice failures.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gameplay_communication_semantics",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Direct Calls, Observers, Commands, and Event Queues\npatterns_architecture | P0 | D4\n\nSelect communication by required result, fan-out, timing, durability, ordering, capacity, lifetime and network boundary.\nWhy: Calling every mechanism decoupled hides re-entrancy, missed state, stale listeners, queue overflow and protocol errors.",
      "x": 7280,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gauntlet_rununreal_target_automation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Gauntlet / RunUnreal Target Automation\nbuild_tools | P2 | D3\n\nUse UE-aware RunUnreal/Gauntlet workflows where appropriate to launch packaged/editor targets, run automation tests and monitor target output.\nWhy: A device lab needs repeatable target orchestration rather than manual launches, but project scenarios and platform adapters remain explicit work.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "mass_queries_processors",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Mass Queries, Processors, Phases, and Access\necs_mass | P2 | D4\n\nDeclare precise presence/read-write requirements and execute ordered processors over contiguous matching chunk views.\nWhy: Query mismatch, hidden writes, per-entity object calls and implicit processor order break correctness and parallel batching.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "mass_representation_lod",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Mass Representation, Simulation LOD, and Hybrid Actors\necs_mass | P2 | D4\n\nSeparate simulation identity from Actor/ISM/no representation and tier visual, simulation and viewer replication fidelity with safe promotion.\nWhy: Rendering/Actor cost can dominate cheap simulation, while dual ownership and LOD thrash corrupt hybrid state.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "mass_structural_traits_templates",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Mass Structural Commands, Traits, Templates, and Spawning\necs_mass | P2 | D3\n\nDefer/batch composition changes and author validated stable entity templates through Traits/configs/spawners.\nWhy: Unsafe mutation invalidates iteration while high-frequency migrations and bad Trait composition erase Mass benefits.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "massai_actor_promotion_contract",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "MassAI Actor Promotion and Dual-Writer Contract\necs_mass | P2 | D4\n\nDefine stable mapping, state transfer, authoritative writer, pooling/invalidation, networking and hysteresis when Mass entities gain Actor representation.\nWhy: Hybrid Mass systems often fail because Mass processors and Actor components both write transform or gameplay state.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "massai_statetree_smartobject_bridge",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "MassAI StateTree and Smart Object Bridge\necs_mass | P2 | D4\n\nRepresent shared crowd activities with durable fragments/context and bridge to Smart Object claim/use/release only when specific world affordances are needed.\nWhy: Mass crowd activity breaks when claim handles, activity state or task progress live only in transient task locals.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "massai_zonegraph_crowd_routes",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "MassAI ZoneGraph and Crowd Routes\necs_mass | P2 | D4\n\nUse Mass fragments/processors with lane/route data for structured crowd movement while keeping NavMesh, avoidance and reservations distinct.\nWhy: Crowd failures are often route/lane, local avoidance, representation or reservation bugs rather than generic pathfinding bugs.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_tasks_targeting_cues",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Ability Tasks, Target Data, and Gameplay Cues\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D3\n\nTasks own asynchronous ability work, target data carries proposals/evidence and cues present cosmetic outcomes without owning truth.\nWhy: Leaked task callbacks, trusted client targets and cosmetic authority create correctness and security failures.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "gas_target_task_cue_safety",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "GAS Target Data, Task, and Cue Safety\ngameplay_ability_system | P2 | D4\n\nValidate target data as evidence, cancel tasks at every wait phase and keep cues cosmetic/idempotent.\nWhy: Trusting target data, leaking tasks or putting gameplay truth in cues creates security, lifecycle and package failures.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "lua_language_capi",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Lua Tables, Metatables, Coroutines, Errors, and C API\nlua | P3 | D3\n\nUse Lua's dynamic table/closure model and virtual C API stack with explicit protected-call, registry, userdata and coroutine discipline.\nWhy: Hidden metamethod calls, retained closures, unbalanced stacks and illegal yield/error paths corrupt integration correctness.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "lua_unreal_gc_plugins",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Lua–UObject Lifetime, GC, Reload, and Plugin Ecosystems\nlua | P3 | D4\n\nBridge separate Lua/Unreal collectors through native ownership, wrapper invalidation and deterministic callback/registry teardown while evaluating exact plugin commits.\nWhy: Cross-runtime cycles, stale wrappers and old reload-generation callbacks survive travel and crash native code.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "input_routing_ui_gas_network",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Input Routing across UI, GAS, and Networking\nmodern_ue5 | P1 | D4\n\nRoute local Enhanced Input events into UI focus, GAS activation adapters and network-safe server intent without confusing sampling with authority.\nWhy: Modern gameplay input often crosses local UI, ability systems and server validation; unclear boundaries create exploits, duplicate activations and modal leaks.",
      "x": 7800,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "navigation_path_following",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "NavMesh, MoveTo, Path Following, and Avoidance\nai_navigation | P0 | D4\n\nNavMesh graph search computes routes; path following executes them; RVO or Detour locally avoids dynamic agents.\nWhy: MoveTo failures and crowd problems span possession, nav data, agent config, requests, movement, and steering layers.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_authority_ownership",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Network Authority, Roles, and Owning Connection\nnetworking | P0 | D4\n\nServer authority owns replicated truth; roles describe local simulation/control; Actor ownership maps RPC and owner policies to a connection.\nWhy: Confusing these relationships causes rejected RPCs, insecure validation, and listen-host-only behaviour.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_property_replication",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Replicated Properties, OnRep, and Conditions\nnetworking | P0 | D4\n\nServer state converges to selected clients through registered replicated properties, optional RepNotify reactions, and audience conditions.\nWhy: It is the baseline mechanism for durable state, late joiners, UI reaction, and bandwidth/privacy policy.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_debug_cvar_workflows",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Network Debug CVars and Evidence Workflow\nnetworking | P1 | D3\n\nUse targeted network debug commands/CVars to validate hypotheses about dormancy, NetGUIDs, subobjects, push model, Fast Arrays and packet behaviour.\nWhy: Network bugs are timing-sensitive; broad logging or folklore fixes hide the true authority, mapping or relevancy problem.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_prediction_rollback_terms",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Prediction, Reconciliation, Rewind, and Rollback Terminology\nnetworking | P1 | D3\n\nUse precise terms for local prediction, server correction/replay, remote smoothing, server rewind and full rollback resimulation.\nWhy: Interview and design discussions become confused when CharacterMovement correction, lag compensation and deterministic rollback are all called rollback.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_character_saved_moves",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Custom CharacterMovement Saved Moves\nnetworking | P2 | D4\n\nMovement-affecting custom state must be captured, compacted, restored, combined safely and validated so client prediction and server reproduction agree.\nWhy: Predicted sprint, dash, slide and wall-run bugs often come from changing movement state outside the saved-move protocol.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_fast_array_push_model",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Fast Array and Push-Model Replication\nnetworking | P2 | D4\n\nUse item-level delta replication and dirty reporting only when stable identity, centralised authoritative mutation and measured benefit justify the complexity.\nWhy: High-churn replicated collections are common interview systems, but missing dirty marks or unstable item IDs create silent desynchronisation.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_iris_replication_awareness",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Iris Replication Awareness\nnetworking | P2 | D2\n\nRecognise Iris as an opt-in experimental replication system and verify project configuration, registered subobjects and fragment requirements before implementation claims.\nWhy: UE5 interviews may mention Iris, but claiming it is automatic or baseline is a version/project error.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_lag_compensation_rewind",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Lag Compensation and Server Rewind\nnetworking | P2 | D4\n\nStore bounded historical hit-relevant server snapshots so authoritative action validation can account for what a client plausibly saw.\nWhy: Responsive shooting and melee require fairness policy, server authority, memory budgeting and abuse resistance under latency.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_component_subobject_replication",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Replicated Components and UObject Subobjects\nnetworking | P2 | D4\n\nReplicate nested state through owning Actors or Actor Components using explicit component replication, subobject networking support, registration and teardown.\nWhy: Modular gameplay systems often need nested replicated state without full Actor identity, and mistakes cause null references, stale raw pointers, missing updates or crashes after GC.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "memory_llm_budget_workflow",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Memory Insights and LLM Budget Workflow\nprofiling_optimisation | P1 | D4\n\nUse LLM/tag checkpoints for ownership and Memory Insights for allocation lifetime, growth, churn and callstack diagnosis.\nWhy: A memory fix depends on whether the issue is capacity, growth, churn, streaming pressure, UObject retention or locality.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_profiling_scalability",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Network Profiling and Replication Scalability\nprofiling_optimisation | P1 | D3\n\nMeasure traffic and server replication cost, then optimise audiences, frequency, state representation, dormancy, and routing architecture.\nWhy: Bandwidth and per-connection Actor consideration grow into latency and server frame failures at scale.",
      "x": 8320,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_relevancy_dormancy",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Actor Relevancy and Network Dormancy\nnetworking | P0 | D4\n\nRelevancy filters Actors per connection; dormancy skips stable Actors while retaining their client instances.\nWhy: These policies dominate scaling and explain missing/destroyed proxies and lost dormant updates.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_rpcs",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Server, Client, and Multicast RPCs\nnetworking | P0 | D4\n\nDirected remote calls carry player intent, targeted responses, or transient fan-out under ownership, relevance, and reliability rules.\nWhy: Wrong routing/reliability produces dropped calls, insecurity, backlog latency, and late-join inconsistency.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "networkprediction_plugin_branch_proof",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "NetworkPrediction Plugin Branch Proof\nnetworking | P2 | D4\n\nVerify target-branch plugin status, headers, model APIs, services and debug CVars before implementing rollback with Epic's NetworkPrediction plugin.\nWhy: Maintained public API pages prove vocabulary but not exact UE5.3-UE5.6 integration signatures or production support.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "network_replication_graph_scaling",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Replication Graph Scaling and Relevance Lists\nnetworking | P2 | D3\n\nUse persistent graph nodes and shared relevance data to reduce per-Actor/per-connection replication list construction when scale justifies it.\nWhy: Large multiplayer worlds fail from server replication CPU and bandwidth policy before individual gameplay code looks expensive.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "networkprediction_cues_side_effects",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Rollback Cues and Side-Effect Safety\nnetworking | P2 | D4\n\nClassify replay-safe cues separately from irreversible authority transactions so prediction and resimulation do not duplicate effects.\nWhy: Rollback bugs often appear as duplicated VFX, camera shakes, damage, rewards or analytics when replay runs the same tick twice.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "networkprediction_state_model",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Rollback Input, Sync, and Aux State Model\nnetworking | P2 | D4\n\nDesign compact replayable input commands, authoritative sync state and versioned aux state for a bounded rollback simulation.\nWhy: Missing or contaminated state causes false convergence, reconcile spam, exploit acceptance and replay with wrong tunables.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "networkprediction_reconcile_proof",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Rollback Reconcile Proof and Profiling\nnetworking | P2 | D4\n\nForce divergence, prove restore/replay/convergence, then measure correction frequency, replay CPU, buffer memory and network payloads.\nWhy: A rollback prototype is not production evidence unless it survives packet conditions, forced correction, side-effect checks and budget measurement.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "niagara_bounds_effecttype_scalability",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Niagara Bounds, Effect Types, Significance, and Scalability\nvfx | P1 | D4\n\nUse correct local/dynamic bounds and semantic Effect Type significance to cull or degrade instances predictably by platform and budget.\nWhy: Small bounds pop, huge bounds defeat culling, and indiscriminate budgets remove critical readable feedback or thrash instances.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "niagara_cpu_gpu_dataflow",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Niagara CPU/GPU Simulation and Gameplay Data Flow\nvfx | P1 | D4\n\nChoose simulation target from population, supported modules/Data Interfaces, CPU interaction/readback, bounds and full CPU/GPU budget while feeding typed presentation data.\nWhy: GPU simulation does not remove CPU/submission cost, and readback or unsupported data paths create latency and correctness traps.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "niagara_collision_renderers_overdraw",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Niagara Collision, Renderers, Materials, and Overdraw\nvfx | P1 | D4\n\nKeep collision cosmetic and select Sprite/Mesh/Ribbon/Light/Component rendering from geometry, submission, lighting, sorting and pixel cost.\nWhy: Particle count hides full-screen translucent overdraw, particle-light multiplication, Component Ticks and delayed/partial collision data.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "niagara_component_pooling_lifetime",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Niagara Component Lifetime, Attachment, Pre-cull, and Pooling\nvfx | P1 | D4\n\nOwn one-shot/persistent Components explicitly and treat auto-destroy, pre-cull and pool release as boundaries requiring null/stale-safe reset logic.\nWhy: Retained pooled pointers, stale parameters/attachment and assumptions about completion cause cross-effect corruption and gameplay coupling.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "niagara_network_debug_profile",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Niagara Networking, Debugging, Profiling, and Lightweight Emitters\nvfx | P1 | D4\n\nReplicate semantics rather than Components, diagnose stack/state/cull causes and profile instance, simulation, submission, GPU graphics and memory before evaluating UE5.4+ lightweight Emitters.\nWhy: Predicted duplicates and stage-blind optimisation break presentation while later features are often assumed available without target proof.",
      "x": 8840,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "pcg_generation_modes_ownership",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "PCG Generation Modes and Output Ownership\nassets_loading | P2 | D4\n\nChoose editor-only, editor-generated, partitioned/hierarchical or runtime PCG with explicit output cleanup, streaming, save/load and authority policy.\nWhy: Runtime generation promises often fail from hitches, duplicated output, cooked-reference gaps, World Partition mismatches or unowned gameplay state.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "pcg_performance_output_cost",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "PCG Performance and Generated Output Cost\nassets_loading | P2 | D4\n\nSeparate graph execution cost from generated Actor/instance/render/collision/nav/streaming/memory cost and prove runtime generation on target hardware.\nWhy: PCG is often blamed for expensive output, while the real problem is spawned representation, collision, lighting, streaming or runtime hitches.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "plugin_runtime_editor_boundaries",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Plugin Runtime/Editor Modules and Load Boundaries\nbuild_tools | P0 | D4\n\nKeep runtime schemas/package targets independent from editor extensions while declaring plugin module hosts, content and legitimate load phases.\nWhy: Editor-only dependency leakage is a common reason clean Game/Server/Shipping builds and packaged content fail.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "physics_movement_rigidbody_ownership",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "CharacterMovement, Kinematic Sweeps, and Rigid-Body Ownership\nphysics | P1 | D4\n\nChoose capsule/sweep movement versus solver-driven bodies and apply force/impulse/mass/inertia/sleep/CCD under one-transform-owner policy.\nWhy: Multiple transform writers and confused force/timestep semantics create jitter, tunnelling and broken prediction.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "physics_materials_ragdoll",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Physical Materials, Physics Assets, and Ragdoll Transitions\nphysics | P1 | D4\n\nUse physical/contact material classification and transfer character ownership through authored Physics Asset bodies/constraints into and out of ragdoll safely.\nWhy: Naive ragdoll toggles create penetration, double impulses, capsule conflicts, attachment and recovery failures.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "physics_timestep_constraints",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Physics Timestep, Substeps, Contacts, and Constraints\nphysics | P1 | D4\n\nBalance solver-step resolution and CPU while designing stable joint frames, degrees, limits, drives and mass ratios.\nWhy: Large steps, wrong local frames and impossible stiffness/mass configurations cause explosions and duplicate callback surprises.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "physics_network_debug_profile",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Networked Physics, Chaos Debugging, and Scalability\nphysics | P2 | D4\n\nKeep server authority, diagnose client/solver divergence and budget queries, awake bodies, contacts, constraints, substeps, callbacks and history.\nWhy: Latency makes contacts diverge, while unbounded bodies/queries/history and cosmetic callbacks overwhelm frame/network budgets.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "platform_mobile_device_profiles",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Mobile Constraints, Device Profiles, and Scalability Proof\nplatform_release | P2 | D4\n\nPrepare mobile/device-tier builds with explicit budgets, device profiles, scalability tiers, mobile rendering policy and target-device evidence.\nWhy: Mobile and constrained platforms fail from thermal, memory, toolchain, renderer and lifecycle realities that editor testing hides.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "platform_lifecycle_cert_matrix",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Platform Lifecycle and Certification-Adjacent Matrix\nplatform_release | P2 | D4\n\nConvert platform lifecycle and certification categories into expected behavior, evidence, owner and risk rows without leaking or inventing confidential requirements.\nWhy: Certification failures often come from unhandled suspend/resume, input, storage, account, network, entitlement, overlay or crash states.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "platform_release_artifact_contract",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Platform Release Artifact and Toolchain Contract\nplatform_release | P2 | D4\n\nArchive exact package, symbols, manifests, logs, metadata, toolchain versions and command parameters for clean-device diagnosis and release proof.\nWhy: Device-only failures and certification issues cannot be diagnosed if the package, symbols, manifests or build commands are not reproducible.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "platform_target_profiling_gate",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Platform Target Profiling and Release Gate\nplatform_release | P2 | D4\n\nMeasure packaged target performance over representative and thermal-length sessions, then gate with percentiles, hitches, memory, I/O and artifact evidence.\nWhy: A build can pass desktop/editor performance gates and still fail target devices from thermals, memory, I/O, package settings or platform profiler findings.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "niagara_stack_parameters",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Niagara Systems, Emitters, Stack, and Parameters\nvfx | P1 | D4\n\nModel one effect as ordered System, Emitter and Particle scripts whose typed scoped attributes are consumed by Renderers.\nWhy: Wrong group, namespace or later attribute writer creates plausible-looking but incorrect simulation that is hard to diagnose.",
      "x": 9360,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "smart_object_authority_scaling",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Smart Object Authority, Debugging, and Scaling\nai_navigation | P2 | D4\n\nValidate durable interaction claims on authority, debug lifecycle phases separately and profile query/path/StateTree work under representative agent counts.\nWhy: Smart Object systems often fail at multiplayer validation or authored scale rather than at single-object happy paths.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "smart_object_lifecycle_claim_release",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Smart Object Query, Claim, Use, and Release Lifecycle\nai_navigation | P2 | D4\n\nSeparate candidate discovery from slot claim, movement/reach validation, behavior execution and release on all success/failure/abort paths.\nWhy: Race conditions and leaked claims are the dominant Smart Object production bugs.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "statetree_execution_dataflow",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "StateTree Execution and Data Flow\nai_navigation | P2 | D4\n\nStateTree selects root-to-leaf active paths, runs active-state tasks, evaluates transitions and binds parameters, context data, evaluators and task output deliberately.\nWhy: Most StateTree failures look like graph logic but actually come from wrong context, premature task completion, missing cleanup or misunderstood transition hierarchy.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 440,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "release_artifacts_symbols_crashes",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Release Artifacts, Symbols, and Crash Proof\nbuild_tools | P2 | D4\n\nArchive packaged output, logs, manifests, metadata and symbols together, then prove crash reporting/symbolication in a packaged build.\nWhy: Production crashes without exact symbols and build metadata are slow or impossible to diagnose.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 660,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "scalability_device_profiles",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Scalability and Device Profiles\nprofiling_optimisation | P1 | D3\n\nExpose quality/cost tiers and platform/device-family configuration while preserving gameplay correctness and readability.\nWhy: The bottleneck and memory envelope move across hardware; one developer-PC configuration cannot serve every target.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 880,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "target_benchmark_capture_contract",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Target Benchmark Capture Contract\nprofiling_optimisation | P1 | D4\n\nDefine build identity, target hardware, quality/profile settings, scenario, warm-up/window, tools, metrics and pass/fail rule before comparing performance.\nWhy: Most optimisation claims fail because the workload or environment changed rather than the code becoming faster.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 1100,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "scripting_reload_security_debug_profile",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Scripting Reload, Security, Networking, Debugging, and Profiling\nscripting | P3 | D4\n\nTreat reload as state migration, expose allow-listed authority-safe APIs and correlate mixed stacks/generations while measuring boundary, GC and retention costs.\nWhy: File replacement leaves old closures/assemblies/callbacks, full reflection defeats sandboxing and single-stack profiles hide boundary failures.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 1320,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "scripting_boundary_adoption",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Scripting Runtime Adoption and Native API Boundaries\nscripting | P3 | D3\n\nAdopt an additional runtime only for a concrete need and expose coarse typed semantic commands/snapshots/events rather than raw engine ownership.\nWhy: A broad chatty API multiplies lifetime, thread, platform, security and maintenance risk across every scripted feature.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 1540,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ue_reflected_native_interfaces",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Reflected Interfaces versus Native Abstract Interfaces\nue_cpp_idioms | P0 | D4\n\nUse UINTERFACE/IInterface for reflected UObject/Blueprint capabilities and ordinary C++ interfaces for pure native boundaries.\nWhy: Interfaces reduce concrete coupling only when the capability contract, state location and Blueprint/native call path are clear.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 1760,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ui_invalidation_render_performance",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UI Invalidation, Rendering, and Performance Diagnosis\nui | P1 | D4\n\nClassify model/update/layout/paint/draw/asset/GPU cost and use invalidation, volatility, virtualisation or Retainers only against evidence.\nWhy: Cargo-cult caching moves cost into render targets/latency while the real binding, layout, asset or overdraw bottleneck remains.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 1980,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ui_model_projection_mvvm",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "UI Model Projection, Events, and MVVM\nui | P1 | D4\n\nProject authoritative gameplay into local display-ready snapshots/deltas while emitting validated intents and bounding pull/Tick work.\nWhy: Direct widget polling and duplicated gameplay truth create stale presentation, authority errors and population-scaled CPU cost.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 2200,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "ui_lists_async_world_widgets",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Virtualised Lists, Async UI Assets, and World Widgets\nui | P1 | D4\n\nTreat rows as recycled views, guard async results by stable identity/generation and scale world widgets through relevance/redraw policy.\nWhy: Stale rows/icons and unbounded per-actor render targets are common correctness and scaling failures.",
      "x": 9880,
      "y": 2420,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "world_data_layers_state_pipeline",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Runtime Data Layers and Durable World State\nworld_building | P2 | D4\n\nUse Runtime Data Layers to present phase/event/progression state while durable truth remains in save, quest or server-owned systems.\nWhy: Layer state can make a world look correct while save/load, late join, replication or content migration is still broken.",
      "x": 10400,
      "y": 0,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    },
    {
      "id": "world_hlod_build_validation",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "World Partition HLOD Build and Validation\nworld_building | P2 | D4\n\nChoose HLOD layers/proxy settings from the measured cost, build proxies in automation and validate far/transition/near behavior in packaged traversal.\nWhy: HLOD can hide distant cost but cannot repair near-field activation, collision, material artefacts, stale build output or streaming hitches.",
      "x": 10400,
      "y": 220,
      "width": 380,
      "height": 160
    }
  ],
